<h4>Clinical microcirculation and the technique of capillaroscopy</h4>
<p>Friday 20 May 2016.  We will be providing equipment and hands on practical demonstrations of microcirculatory capillaroscopy techniques at this Royal Society of Medicine event.</p>
<a href="https://www.rsm.ac.uk/events/events-listing/2015-2016/sections/vascular-medicine-section/vag01-clinical-microcirculation-and-the-technique-of-capillaroscopy.aspx">
<img src="rsm2016.jpg" width=25%></a>
<p>Venue 	</p>
<p>Royal Society of Medicine</p>
<p>1 Wimpole Street</p>
<p>LONDON</p>
<p>W1G 0AE</p>
<a href="https://www.rsm.ac.uk/events/events-listing/2015-2016/sections/vascular-medicine-section/vag01-clinical-microcirculation-and-the-technique-of-capillaroscopy.aspx">
click here for further information at the RSM website.</a>

<h4>BBC Horizon "Are we still evolving?"</h4>
<p>1st March 2011. Tonight at 9pm BBC2, BBC's Horizon TV program "Are we still evolving?" will feature the new <a href="hvcs.html">HVCS</a> handheld
CapiScope Video Capillaroscopy System being used by Professor Cynthia Beall in the mountainous Himalayas of Nepal.<p>


<p>A system was required that was battery powered and lightweight and easily portable to be used in very remote mountainous Khumbu region in the Himalayas.</p>

<img src="Beall-capiscope-Khumbu-Nepal-2010.jpg" alt="Professor Cynthia Beall in Khumbu Nepal using KK Technology HVCS Handheld CapiScope" width=200>
<p>Photo copyright Cynthia Beall 2010.</p>

<p>The program includes a brief scene showing the <a href="hvcs.html">HVCS</a> in use.  
You can watch it <a href="horizon.avi">here.</a></p>
<p></p>
<img src="cynthia-beall.png" alt="Professor Cynthia Beall" width=33%>
<img src="beall-and-sherpa.png" alt="Professor Cynthia Beall using HVCS on Sherpa" width=33%>
<img src="credits.png" alt="Professor Cynthia Beall" width=33%>


